05097nam a22008055i 9780231550284DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019005951  a97802315502847 a10.7312/brad193382doi  a(DE-B1597)537598  a(OCoLC)1119625763  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJF801b.B69 2019 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320.012231 aBradley, Arthur, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnbearable Life :bA Genealogy of Political Erasure /cArthur Bradley. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInsurrections: Critical Studies in Religion, Politics, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. Unbearable: Foucault and the Birth of Nihilopolitics -- t2. Ungood: Augustine’s City of Cacus -- t3. Untimely Ripped: Macbeth’s Children -- t4. Uncommon: Hobbes’s Martyrs -- t5. Incorruptible: Robespierre and the Already Dead -- t6. Unleashed: Schmitt and the Katechon -- t7. Undead: Benjamin and the Past to Come -- tCONCLUSION -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn ancient Rome, any citizen who had brought disgrace upon the state could be subject to a judgment believed to be worse than death: damnatio memoriae, condemnation of memory. The Senate would decree that every trace of the citizen’s existence be removed from the city as if they had never existed in the first place. Once reserved for individuals, damnatio memoriae in different forms now extends to social classes, racial and ethnic groups, and even entire peoples. In modern times, the condemned go by different names—“enemies of the people;” the “missing,” the “disappeared,” “ghost” detainees in “black sites”—but they are subject to the same fate of political erasure.Arthur Bradley explores the power to render life unlived from ancient Rome through the War on Terror. He argues that sovereignty is the power to decide what counts as being alive and what does not: to make life “unbearable,” unrecognized as having lived or died. In readings of Augustine, Shakespeare, Hobbes, Robespierre, Schmitt, and Benjamin, Bradley asks: What is the “life” of this unbearable life? How does it change and endure across sovereign time and space, from empires to republics, from kings to presidents? To what extent can it be resisted or lived otherwise? A profoundly interdisciplinary and ambitious work, Unbearable Life rethinks sovereignty, biopolitics, and political theology to find the radical potential of a life that neither lives or dies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aBiopolitics. 0aCitizenship. 0aCollective memoryxPolitical aspects. 0aExpatriation. 0aPolitical theology. 0aSovereignty. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2019 Englishz978311061055008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2019z9783110606423oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/brad1933840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231550284423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231550284.jpg  a978-3-11-061055-0  EBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065195-9  Columbia Univer